rememberedPersonSummary.name: Caroline Longden-Boole
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

On Sunday 15th November, Caroline lost her battle with cancer. She had fought bravely for 18 months and tried everything to stay with us, her family and friends. 

The help and support that she received from Macmillan throughout her illness was amazing, and I know that they are still there for us if we need them. We know that Caroline would like us to support this wonderful charity and be able to give something back so that they can carry on supporting others in their times of need.

Caroline was only 41 when she was taken from us and leaves behind 5 beautiful children. We are all bewildered and devastated by her loss and are trying to come to terms with how unfair life can be. We know that she wouldn't want us to be sad at her passing but celebrate her life which she always tried to live to the full. She has been described as strong willed, determined and funny, a lovely woman and so full of life, a beautiful and honest lady and so many people have lovely memories of her.

Unfortunately, we cannot invite many people to the funeral, so we are asking for a small donation to Macmillan as a way of remembering Caroline until we can all come together for a proper celebration of her life. We know her life touched so many people so really hope we can help her to give something back to such a wonderful cause.

Thank you for all the lovely kind words of support we have received, we really do appreciate every one of them.
title: Remembering Caroline
pageSummary: To remember the life of our friend and sister Caz because they provided help and support when she needed it

story:
This is a Just Giving page, set up in memory of Lynn Kirkland who sadly lost her battle with cancer on 24th October 2020.



We have chosen to raise money for two different charities:- MacMillan Cancer Support and Kilbryde Hospice.



We kindly asked for no flowers at the funeral and instead, requested any donations made to our chosen charities. Both of these charities were close to my mums heart and have also supported us throughout this difficult time.

We would like to do something positive during our time of sadness and would therefore be very grateful for any donations made to help us raise money for these two organisations.


Thank you very much for your support.


Gillian

story:
Hello everyone,

i would just like to say this is a COMPLETE SUPRISE so no messages to my dad about his state or about the walk please, we are still adjusting to the news ourselves  

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

As many of you know my dad was rushed into hospital after a sudden decline one day on a journey to see family in September. We have recently found out that that decline was caused due to a stage 4 malignant brain cancer. This walk will be honour of my dad this type of brain cancer has no cure and i hope that this money will eventually lead to the finding of a treatment which can extend the period of life or even cure. So that one day nobody has to go through what my dad has. 

Any donation, will be so appreciated have had so many messages already even of people wanting to get involved. If thats the case we will see what restrictions are in place when i plan to do this wal 19th december even if it is walking in groups of 6 i will try to make that possible. I will be printing out all donations to show my dad on christmas day as this is his last day of treatment.

So much love to you all

story:
In September 2020 my dad was rushed into hospital in which we thought was a stroke.  Turned out that my dad had a brain tumour which later turned out to be Stage 4 Brain Cancer this type of cancer is fatal, there is no cure. My aim is to raise as much money as possible as a surprise to him to tell him and show him photos from the day etc on christmas day as he will be recovering from treatment  

THIS IS A COMPLETE SUPRISE and my dad is really quiet about his struggles  So absolutely NO messages to him please and on christmas day i will have a print out of all donations in a massive card. If anyone is interested in being involved and walking alongside me let me know, any donation is honestly appreciated with all my heart. I have already had so many lovely messages that i am in tears just writing this.

In 2018 I was proud to have raised almost £2000 for Macmillan by shaving my beloved hair off. This time I am determined to reach my target but I need your help. After running helping me get through a really tough time during lockdown, both physically and mentally, I will be running 10km EVERYDAY for 10 days. Thank you for your support, anything you can donate is wholeheartedly appreciated.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Each year, the TCM Group run a charity fundraising campaign in the run up to Christmas. 2020 has been a challenging year, and while our business has retained its success, we are very aware of the challenges faced by others, especially charities.

As part of our campaign this year, we have chosen The British Heart Foundation as one two charities we would like to support. Funds will be raised through several sources:

- An initial one-off donation of £250 from TCM.

- For every Mediation and Investigation (our two main products) we sell during December, we will donate an additional £50.

- We are also running a social media hashtag campaign #ThumbsUpForResolution to promote the widespread benefits of early conflict resolution in the workplace. For each person who posts a picture of themselves, with their thumbs up and this hashtag, we will donate an additional £1.

- We would also like to welcome additional personal or corporate donations from anyone wishing to contribute.

Thank you for your generosity. From all of us here at The TCM Group, we wish you a Merry Christmas and a Happy New Year!
title: The TCM Group's Christmas Charity Campaign for the British Heart Foundation

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Bernard Crimmins
story:
Bernard was a much loved Husband, Father Grandfather and Great-Grandfather.

He served as a Corporal in the Cameron Highlanders and was in the Second World War in the desert in Libya, then in Italy and ended up in Austria when it ended. He also took part in the Suez crisis and left the full time Army in 1952. He then served 5 years as a reservist with the Liverpool Scottish.

He is survived by his wife Josie, his children; Peter, Jill, Diane and Sue. His grandchildren Claire; Amy; Joel, Connor; Scarlett and Leonie and his great-grandchildren Chelsea, Kenny & Ruby.
title: In loving memory of Bernard Crimmins

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas Collection 

Help us as we aim to raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas! 

During December the four-legged volunteers of the Sunderland Fundraising Group would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at collections and events in your community.  

Due to the current situation, we’re not able to be out as much this 
festive season, and we know you will miss seeing our life-changing doggy volunteers! We’re hoping you will help us and donate to our ‘12 Guide Dogs of Christmas’ Collection as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships!  

It costs over £56,000 to fund the lifetime cost of a guide dog. Please consider donating £12 during our 12-day collection so we can fund 12 new life-changers this Christmas.  

We appreciate that times are difficult, but for people with sight loss, 
social isolation can be their everyday. You can help them feel less alone, now and in the future. 

Don’t forget to send it on through Facebook, WhatsApp, email or text and get your friends and family involved too. 

Thank you and Merry Christmas!
title: Sunderland 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas

story:
Bex and Hart have decided to take part in the 100 for Guide Dogs Challenge along with our 4 legged friend Bambi.  We aim to raise £300 by the 30th November 20.

We began the challenge on 17th November 20 so we have only given ourselves 14 days to complete. 

We are currently 7 days in, 60 miles complete so far and recording our progress via Strava, which we will update this page with.

Please help where you can.

Thankyou for reading.

Bex, Hart and our 4 legged friend Bambi. 

100 for Guide Dogs is your challenge, your way. You can choose to Run100, Cycle100 or Swim100 between 1 July and 31 November. However you take on your 100, get sponsored to do it and help us supporting people living with sight loss. You could complete 100 metres, 100 minutes, 100 days be creative!The sponsorship money you raise will make a difference. £100 could pay for five hours' training at a Guide Dogs training school.It's thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services, like our guide dogs, to people with sight loss. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!#TeamGuideDogs

rememberedPersonSummary.name: William Crofts
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Our Grandad sadly passed away Friday 13th. He was loved by so many and will be missed more than words can say. I know many have been asking about flowers and donations and as a family we have decided to raise funds for a charity close to his heart- Guide Dogs UK. 

As everyone knows Grandad loved dogs ( especially his golden labs), he had three dogs growing up Toby, Sheba and Lady. As well as leaving behind a big loving family he also left behind Dexter who has been moping around looking for him. 

Instead of flowers, it would mean the world however large or small if we can raise a little money for this charity , in his memory ... this would make him so proud.
title: In memory of William Crofts

story:
Ready… get set… Run off Christmas! In January I am Kickstarting my 2021 with a healthy outlook and the chance to help support the incredible work that takes place every day at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH).

Running off Christmas is my new year challenge. I will run 31 miles throughout January; for a lot of people that would be easy but for all of you who know me well, will know I struggle to run up the stairs let alone commit to running a minium of 1 mile a day!! 🏃‍🤣👍 But now with the news that I am pre-diabetic it's time to get fit whilst helping an amazing charity at the same time. So please donate only what you can afford & wish me luck 🍀🙏 xx

story:
Hello

I'm President of Cambridge Chartered Insurance Institute (CII) and our biggest charity fundraiser of the year is normally our annual dinner in December. This year was due to be extra special as it is the 100th anniversary of our institute being established. 

Due to obvious reasons, we can't hold the get together this year. With this in mind, I wanted to recognise the centenary by raising funds for charity at the same time... and running off some mince pies.

During the month of December, I'll be running 100km for 100 years of Cambridge CII. My fellow council member Mark Hassle is also taking part by cycling 100km. 

We are raising money for Cancer Research UK. Over recent years, several family members have battled cancer and so this is a cause very close to my heart. 

All donations are really appreciated by me and Cancer Research UK. 

Thanks for reading and your support,

Nick Carson

story:
Myself, Kyle, Ashley and Dylan are raising money for charity by running the vertical height of the 5 tallest mountains in the world. Makalu is 8.46km, Lhotse is 8.51km, Kangchenjunga is 8.58km, K2 is 8.61km and Mount Everest is 8.85km. 
All team members will run the height of Mount Everest and 1 other mountain. Each member will run an average distance of 17.5 km.
We will be running these distances over several days and will start our challenge on the 30th November 2020.

Thank you for your support.

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
charity.registrationNumber: 207994 (England & Wales) and SC038731 (Scotland)
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Anne Dinnis
story:
Our hospice is a warm and welcoming place, supporting people in Edinburgh and their loved ones with expert care, every day of the year. 

Our doctors, nurses, physiotherapists and social workers are supported by a team of volunteers, who play a vital role in the running of the hospice.

Some of the people we support stay in our in-patient unit, where relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night and stay with their loved ones if they wish to.

We also support local people with clinics, therapies and activities during the day  including one-to-one care, groups and things like reiki and massage. 

As well as people with a terminal illness, we also support carers and families with things like bereavement support groups where people can share their experiences and feelings.

Thank you for supporting us, and helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in Edinburgh get the care and support they need.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Claudia Ann Hanson
story:
Firstly, thank you for visiting this page.

My auntie Claude, as she was known, sadly lost her third battle with cancer at the end October 2020. Marie Curie were a huge support not just to her but also to all the family during this very difficult time. The care and kindness that was offered during the last few days was outstanding.

I am wanting to raise as much money as possible for Marie Curie in memory of Claude. If you haven’t heard of them, they provide care and support for people living with any terminal illness, and their families. There is a clear link between Coronavirus lockdown and treatments/operations/diagnosis being delayed, so now is a good time to be raising money for them. 2020 has not been an easy year for charities with fund raising events having been cancelled.

Starting on Tuesday 1st December, I will be running 5k through the Yorkshire countryside every single day of the month, with my loyal Labrador Bramble. I will upload my routes daily to show my progress and hopefully improve my time!

Please donate if you can to this wonderful charity.

Very many thanks,

Ali & Bramble
title: Ali's 5k Every Day in December 2020

story:
This year, instead of a Head Office Christmas party, we're inviting colleagues to be in with the chance of winning some incredible prizes with our Head Office Christmas raffle, all whilst supporting our charity partner Marie Curie.

We are hoping to raise at least £1,600 to sponsor a Registered Nurse for the £12 days of Christmas, so they can help the people they care for make the most of what could be their final Christmas with their loved ones.

To buy a ticket all you need to do is donate what you would have spent at the Christmas party.

Mince pie – donate £3 – one ticket. Your ticket is the equivalent of heating a hospice for one hour. Meaning patients and their families feel warm and comfortable, even on the nippiest of days. 

Pint of lager – donate £5 – two tickets. Your tickets are the equivalent of heating a hospice for one hour AND a glass of wine for a patient at one of our hospices, because enjoying a favourite tipple brings a smile to peoples faces and is a treat many look forward to

Class of prosecco – donate £7 – three tickets. Your tickets are the equivalent of heating a hospice for one hour AND a glass of wine for two patients at one of our hospices.

Please include your full name and department in your donation message so we can track who has purchased a ticket.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
RNLI Newhaven is raising funds to keep its lifeboat afloat and ready to launch in this difficult year and beyond.

Newhaven Lifeboat is one of our South East lifeboats,  protecting its community through their 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the availability of their all weather Severn Class lifeboat, modern station and volunteer crew. 

The beaches of East Sussex are enjoyed by millions of people from across the country every year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

The RNLI station at Newhaven relies on donations from the public to continue saving lives at sea. We have been busier than ever during this extraordinary year when usual fundraising activity has not been possible.

We thank you for your support.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Your generosity this Christmas will help bring our volunteer crew home safely to their loved ones. Volunteers on the frontline launch into winter winds, freezing waters and huge waves. They need training and kit plus extra PPE, like masks and gloves. And as a charity, the RNLI relies on kind donations to
provide them with this. But income is expected to be down by millions this year.

So as a special Christmas gift, will you consider donating to the RNLI instead of sending physical Christmas cards this year? You can end this year with kindness, knowing that you’ve helped keep lifeboat volunteers ready and able to save lives. They are so grateful to have you beside them.

story:
Thank you visiting my Just Giving page. 

RNLI lifeboats in the Ireland protect hundreds of communities through their 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
RNLI relies on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea and on inland waters - your donation to this page will help support the running of lifeboat stations in Ireland.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Your generosity this Christmas will help bring our volunteer crew home safely to their loved ones. Volunteers on the frontline launch into winter winds, freezing waters and huge waves. They need training and kit plus extra PPE, like masks and gloves. And as a charity, the RNLI relies on kind donations to provide them with this. But income is expected to be down by millions this year.

So as a special Christmas gift, will you consider donating to the RNLI instead of sending physical Christmas cards this year? You can end this year with kindness, knowing that you’ve helped keep lifeboat volunteers ready and able to save lives. They are so grateful to have you beside them.
title: RNLI Christmas ecard

story:
WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.

Your support is much appreciated.

Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

story:
WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.

Your support is much appreciated.

Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
